<h1>Problem 10</h1>
    <a href="../amc10b-2025.html">← Back to AMC 10B 2025</a>

<div class="section">
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Category:</b> <span>Number Theory</span>
    </div>
</div>
<p>Let $f(n)=n^3-5n^2+2n+8$ and $g(n)=n^3-6n^2+5n+12.$ What is the sum of all integers $n$ such that $\tfrac{f(n)}{g(n)}$ is an integer?</p>
<div class="options">
$$\textbf{(A) } 2  \qquad \textbf{(B) } 3 \qquad \textbf{(C) } 4 \qquad \textbf{(D) } 5 \qquad \textbf{(E) } 6$$
</div>
<div class="section">
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Difficulty:</b> <span>35/100 - A straightforward problem  </span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Core Concepts:</b> <span> Divisibility rules.</span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Challenges:</b> <span> Competitors may waste time bashing combinations if unaware of divisibility rules. </span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Techniques:</b> <span> Divisibility rules for $9$ and $4$ give that $3B+2A$ is a multiple of $9$ and $\underline B~\underline A$ is a multiple of $4$. Identifying restrictions about $A$ reveals the final answer. </span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Error-prone Steps:</b> <span> N/A </span>
    </div>
    <div class="ideal-time">
        <b>Ideal Time:</b>
        <div class="ideal-list">
            Experienced: ≤ 1 min<br>
            Intermediate: ≤ 2-3 min<br>
            Beginner: ≤ 4 min
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
